<div id="review_810235676" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/810235676" />
    <a title="Trena" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1253638-trena"><img alt="Trena" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/810235676?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trena" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trena" href="/user/show/1253638-trena">Trena</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Trena by: </span>
      Sheryl
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer810235676" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4553052033551827660">In addition to giving a terrifying minute-by-minute account of the fire, Von Drehle puts the Triangle Shirtwaist Fire into its larger social context of strikes, socialism, Tammany, and labor reform. Though I knew a bit about the fire itself, I didn&apos;t know much about labor history of the time and the author does a nice job of keeping the pace going while still explaining the philosophy and tensions. There are parts that seem extraneous, but it was overall a well-written and engaging book. I appre</span>
  <span id="freeText4553052033551827660" style="display:none">In addition to giving a terrifying minute-by-minute account of the fire, Von Drehle puts the Triangle Shirtwaist Fire into its larger social context of strikes, socialism, Tammany, and labor reform. Though I knew a bit about the fire itself, I didn't know much about labor history of the time and the author does a nice job of keeping the pace going while still explaining the philosophy and tensions. There are parts that seem extraneous, but it was overall a well-written and engaging book. I appreciated that he made the effort to create a definitive list of the victims, which had apparently never been done before, with their name, age, address, and the relative who identified them.<br /><br />The major lesson is: NO FIRE IN THE SEWING ROOM EVER. Not that I would have fire in the sewing room, but a stray ash from a cigar or a not-fully-blown out match in a box of light cotton scraps tore out of control within minutes and killed 140 people.<br /><br />Shortly after finishing, I had a trip planned for New York. I decided it was a good time to go to the <a href="http://www.tenement.org/" rel="nofollow noopener">Tenement Museum</a>, which can only be visited as a tour. I chose the Sweatshop Workers tour to go with this book. It was a great combination to have the history fresh in my mind and then see the actual space where the Triangle workers would have lived and hear more of their social context. I recommend both the book and the museum, and especially as a pair.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4553052033551827660" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


