  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1264770855" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1264770855" />
    <a title="Eileen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28117212-eileen"><img alt="Eileen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483503975p2/28117212.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1264770855?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eileen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eileen" href="/user/show/28117212-eileen">Eileen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1264770855" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17608564350090584268"><br/>This was a very well detailed and insightful account of the historic 1911 fire at the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory which led to revolutionary changes in the field of labor law (as suggested by the book&apos;s title and summary). It was also a revealing portrait of the lives of immigrants (particularly those of women) who worked in the New York City garment industry in the early 1900&apos;s.<br/><br/>The first four chapters of this book begin by providing a snapshot of what New York City was like in the early 20th Ce</span>
  <span id="freeText17608564350090584268" style="display:none"><br />This was a very well detailed and insightful account of the historic 1911 fire at the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory which led to revolutionary changes in the field of labor law (as suggested by the book's title and summary). It was also a revealing portrait of the lives of immigrants (particularly those of women) who worked in the New York City garment industry in the early 1900's.<br /><br />The first four chapters of this book begin by providing a snapshot of what New York City was like in the early 20th Century from a political, social, and economic perspective. Next, the book offers both universal and individual views of what life was like for women working in the garment industry before, and during, the time that the seeds of labor activism were planted, took root, and quickly flourished. Not surprisingly, employers grappled and spontaneously experimented with how to undermine the galvanized efforts of both the women who were working in the garment industry and the women outside the industry who had both an interest in the labor cause as well as the social, political, and financial capital to support the effort. The perspective of both the employer and the employee on each side of the labor fight, in this relatively uncharted territory, is successfully portrayed in the book.<br /><br />The next section of the book succinctly details the tragic and chaotic circumstances of the fire itself. The level of detail allows the reader to visualize the events, moment by moment, and sympathize with each individual facing the many obstacles that existed during the collective effort to escape. The intimately personal experiences of the victims reveal a large web of failure points, ranging from architectural design to communication protocol, all of which were at once magnified when seconds and minutes were the difference between life and death. Sadly, it was noted that the fire could have been prevented had it not been for employer complacency and greed which gave rise to the many workplace deficiencies. The ramifications of the tragedy, and the changes that were required, were broad in scope in that they encompassed many aspects of business, politics, and law. Details of the reform activities and the strategically interesting (and at times incredulous) courtroom trial of the factory owners are described in the book's final chapters.<br /><br />Overall, although this is a tragic story, it is an excellent case study in demonstrating the necessity, and evolution, of satisfactory industrial workplace conditions. The fact that many individuals are specifically identified is helpful in that it provides the opportunity for further reading about those of interest. The story underscores the importance of today's fire safety and emergency management planning as well as the essential laws/regulations in many areas related to the workplace. It is always unfortunate when it takes a tragedy with lost lives to highlight weaknesses in an organizational system and bring about change. At the same time, there is a bit of reassurance in knowing that the lost lives ultimately manifested in future lives being saved as the result of implemented changes which we can see evidence of today and can comparatively label as significant progress.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17608564350090584268" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

